          "title": "The collapsing of social hierarchy",
          "body": "The chapter is a quiet revolution in the social structures of the Greco-Roman world. **Masters and slaves** (4:1, completing 3:22-25) stand together under one heavenly *Kurios*. **Onesimus the runaway slave** (4:9) is named alongside the apostolic envoy as 'faithful and beloved brother' and 'one of your number' — the Colossian church must receive him back as family, the very plea developed in Philemon. **Nympha** (4:15) hosts a church. **A Jew and a physician**, **a former deserter (Mark) and a fellow prisoner (Aristarchus)** all bear the same title: *sunergos* (fellow worker, 4:11) and *adelphos* (brother). Paul does not theorize about the gospel collapsing hierarchy — he names the names."
